# Emily Python Backend Rules

## Architecture
- Emily is a multi-agent AI voice system. Code is organized into layers: perception, agents, llm, memory, plugins, voice, api, core
- Agents inherit from `BaseAgent` (agents/base.py) and register in `agents/registry.py`
- Tools inherit from `BaseTool` (plugins/base.py) with mandatory `execute()` and `dry_run()` methods
- All prompts live in `llm/prompt_builder.py` — inline prompt strings anywhere else are bugs
- Inter-agent communication uses `AgentBus` (core/bus.py) with structured Message envelopes

## Style & Conventions
- Type-annotate ALL function signatures — parameters and return types
- Every function must have a docstring (Args, Returns, Raises sections for public APIs)
- Use `from __future__ import annotations` for forward references
- Prefer `dataclasses` or `pydantic` models over plain dicts for structured data
- Never use mutable default arguments

## Async & I/O
- All route handlers, agent methods, and bus callbacks must be async
- Never do blocking I/O inside an async function — use `asyncio.to_thread` or background tasks
- ZeroMQ operations go through `zmq.asyncio` — never use sync zmq
- Latency budget: STT < 300ms, LLM first token < 1s (fast_model), TTS first audio < 200ms

## Error Handling
- Use specific exception types, never bare `except:`
- Log exceptions with `log.exception(...)` via structlog
- API routes: raise `HTTPException` with structured `detail`
- Agents: return error via `ToolResult.fail()` — never silently swallow failures

## Imports
- Group: stdlib, third-party, local — separated by blank lines
- Use absolute imports for cross-module references
- Lazy imports for optional heavy dependencies (torch, faster_whisper, etc.)

## Security
- PII scrubber must run before any disk write of user data
- Tool sandbox (`bubblewrap`) for code execution — no network, path allowlist only
- Audit log entries for all security-sensitive operations
- Never log request bodies that may contain PII or credentials
